  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "The difference between \"shall\" and \"will\" lies primarily in their formality and regional usage, particularly in British English vs. American English. Historically, they were used to express different shades of meaning, but this distinction is largely blurred in modern usage.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n**Historically (and Still Used in Formal Settings, Primarily British English):**\n\n*   **Shall:** Used in the first person (I, we) to express a future action, obligation, or suggestion.\n    *   **Future Action (Less Common Now):**  \"I shall go to the store later.\" (More formal than \"I will go...\")\n    *   **Obligation (Directive):**  \"You shall not pass!\" (This emphasizes a command or rule)\n    *   **Suggestion/Offer:** \"Shall we dance?\" (A polite way to propose something)\n*   **Will:** Used in the second and third person (you, he, she, it, they) to express a future action, a prediction, or a promise.\n    *   **Future Action:** \"He will arrive tomorrow.\"\n    *   **Prediction:** \"It will rain later.\"\n    *   **Promise:** \"I will always love you.\"\n\n**Modern Usage (and American English):**\n\n*   **Will:** This is the default future tense auxiliary verb and is used in *all* persons (I, you, he, she, it, we, they) in most situations.  It expresses intention, prediction, or a simple future action. \"I will go to the store,\" \"You will go to the store,\" \"They will go to the store.\"\n*   **Shall:**  Its use is significantly reduced. It's mostly found:\n    *   **In formal legal documents:** To express an obligation or requirement (e.g., \"The tenant shall maintain the property\").\n    *   **In questions with \"I\" or \"we\" to make suggestions or offers:** \"Shall we go out for dinner?\"\n    *   **In very formal British English:**  Though even here, it's becoming less common.\n\n**Key Differences Summarized:**\n\n| Feature        | Shall                                  | Will                                     |\n| -------------- | -------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n| Person         | Primarily 1st person (I, we) historically  | Primarily 2nd and 3rd person historically, now used for all |\n| Usage          | Formal, legal, suggestions/offers      | General future tense, intention, prediction |\n| Regional Usage | More common (though declining) in British English | Standard in American English           |\n\n**When in Doubt:**\n\n*   In most modern situations, **\"will\" is the safer and more common choice**, especially in American English.\n*   If you're unsure, especially in formal writing or legal contexts, it's best to research the specific requirements or guidelines for the document you are creating.\n*   For questions like \"Shall we...?\" or \"Shall I...?\", \"shall\" remains acceptable for making suggestions.\n\n**Example:**\n\n*   **Formal (British English):** \"I shall be pleased to accept your invitation.\"\n*   **Informal (General Usage):** \"I will be happy to accept your invitation.\"\n\nIn conclusion, the distinction between \"shall\" and \"will\" has largely faded, with \"will\" becoming the dominant form. However, knowing the historical context and specific uses of \"shall\" can help you understand its presence in formal documents and some British English expressions.\n",
